tool.name: BlockStatisticsRasterTool

param.name: raster_table
param.dialogReference: This is the input table, usually the results table generated by the ‘Geodata > Search’ tool, but it can be any table with a field containing the full path to the raster datasets you want to process with this tool. If the results table is a DBF, or a table in an ESRI File Geodatabase, then you can select a subset of rows in ArcMap and only those rows will be processed by the tool.

param.name: raster_table_field_0
param.dialogReference: Select the field from the 'Table for Rasters' that contains the full path to the raster datasets you want to have processed by the tool.

param.name: statistics_type
param.expression: {MEAN | MAJORITY | MAXIMUM | MEDIAN | MINIMUM | RANGE | STD | SUM | VARIETY}
param.dialogReference:
The statistic type to be calculated, the default statistic type is MEAN. Select from the following:

  • MEAN — Calculates the mean (average value) of the cells in the neighborhood.

  • MAJORITY — Calculates the majority (value that occurs most often) of the cells in the neighborhood.

  • MAXIMUM — Calculates the maximum (largest value) of the cells in the neighborhood.

  • MEDIAN — Calculates the median of the cells in the neighborhood.

  • MINIMUM — Calculates the minimum (smallest value) of the cells in the neighborhood.

  • MINORITY — Calculates the minority (value that occurs least often) of the cells in the neighborhood.

  • RANGE — Calculates the range (difference between largest and smallest value) of the cells in the neighborhood.

  • STD — Calculates the standard deviation of the cells in the neighborhood.

  • SUM — Calculates the sum (total of all values) of the cells in the neighborhood.

  • VARIETY — Calculates the variety (the number of unique values) of the cells in the neighborhood.

param.name: ignore_nodata
param.dialogReference:
Denotes whether NoData values are ignored by the statistic calculation. Select from:

  • DATA — Specifies that if a NoData value exists within a block neighborhood, the NoData value will be ignored. Only cells within the neighborhood that have data values will be used in determining the output value. This is the default.

  • NODATA — Specifies that if any cell in a neighborhood has a value of NoData, the output for each cell in the corresponding block will receive NoData. With this option, the presence of a NoData value implies that there is insufficient information to determine the statistic value for the neighborhood.

param.name: output_workspace
param.dialogReference:
This is the location for the Grid Garage results table containing the list of raster datasets processed by the tool as well as any data outputs. If the tool encounters any errors when processing the input raster datasets then a second results table will be generated, with a "_FAIL" suffix, listing the input raster datasets that failed and any ESRI error messages.

If you have set the ArcGIS ‘Workspace' parameter in the 'Geoprocessing > Environment' Settings then this path will be used as the default. You can use this default path or click the folder button to select a new output location which can be a folder or File Geodatabase. If you specify a folder then the Results Table will be written to a comma-delimited (CSV) text file, if you specify a File Geodatabase it will be written as a Geodatabase Table.

param.name: result_table_name
param.dialogReference:
You can choose to use the default table name or specify a different name for the Grid Garage results table. The Grid Garage results table contains the list of raster datasets processed by the tool.

If the tool encounters any errors when processing any of the raster datasets then a second results table will be generated, with a "_FAIL" suffix, listing the input raster datasets that failed and any ESRI error messages. If you choose a folder for the Output Workspace then the result table will be written to a comma-delimited (CSV) text file which will not allow you to select rows for processing when using the table as input for other Grid Garage Tools.

Result Table file name: The default name will always take the form of “DescribeGeodataTool_date_time”, where ‘date’ and ‘time’ are the date and time that the tool was run.

tool.summary:
This tool Partitions the input into non-overlapping blocks and calculates the statistic of the values within each block. The value is assigned to all of the cells in each block in the output.

This is illustrated in Figure 7in the Grid Garage user manual. If the data type of the input raster is floating point then only a subset of the statistics will be available (MEAN, MAXIMUM, MINIMUM, RANGE, STD and SUM. For more detailed help see ESRI Help for the ‘Block Statistics (Spatial Analyst)’ tool.
